# Chapter 2 — Piano

The piano is the instrument most readers already know how to
imagine. It is also the instrument whose synthesis is the most
familiar template — a hammer strikes a string, the string rings, the
ring decays. Everything else about the piano — the pedals, the
articulation, the resonance — is a modification of that basic
event.

This chapter teaches the piano as a voice on the runtime's roster: how it
is synthesized (a physical-model hammered-string profile), how it is
articulated (the difference between a struck note, a pedaled note,
and a released note), and how it is played (from a single note to a
full chord with the sustain pedal down).

*The piano is the instrument I reach for when I want the reader to
hear something and immediately know what it is. Every reader has a
piano in their head — they might not know a shakuhachi from a
koto, but they know a piano. That familiarity is a gift and a
constraint. If the piano sounds wrong, the reader will notice
before they know they noticed.*

## 2.1 One note, unarticulated

The smallest piano program. Select the grand piano and play a
middle C for a quarter beat.

```scheme
(begin
  (synth/select 'grand-piano)
  (play/note 'c4 'quarter))
```

You hear one soft, clear middle C. It has a hard onset (the hammer
strike), a bright first moment (the initial partials ringing), and
a decay that fades over about a second. That is the piano's
fundamental unit: hammer, string, decay.

## 2.2 A struck note versus a legato note

By default, `play/note` on the piano gives you a struck articulation
— hammer down, string rings, decay. `play/articulation!` changes
that. Legato gives you a slightly softer onset and a longer sustain
before decay begins.

```scheme
(begin
  (synth/select 'grand-piano)
  (play/articulation! 'natural)
  (play/note 'c4 'quarter)
  (play/articulation! 'legato)
  (play/note 'e4 'quarter)
  (play/articulation! 'staccato)
  (play/note 'g4 'quarter))
```

Three notes, three articulations. The natural C is the plain
struck note from 2.1. The legato E is slightly rounder — the
onset is softer and the note sustains longer before its decay. The
staccato G is short and detached — the note is cut off well before
its natural decay would have finished. You will hear the difference
most clearly in the *length* of the sustained portion of each note.

## 2.3 Dynamics — the loudness of the strike

On a real piano, dynamics come from the velocity of the key strike:
harder strike, louder note, brighter tone (more high partials).
`play/dynamics!` mirrors this. `pp` is soft and dark; `ff` is loud
and bright.

```scheme
(begin
  (synth/select 'grand-piano)
  (play/dynamics! 'pp)
  (play/note 'c4 'quarter)
  (play/dynamics! 'mf)
  (play/note 'c4 'quarter)
  (play/dynamics! 'ff)
  (play/note 'c4 'quarter))
```

Three C4s at three dynamics. The soft one is barely there and warm.
The medium one is the reference. The loud one has more edge and
brightness. On a real piano, this is not just loudness — the high
partials come in with the strike velocity. The synthesis profile
models this: `ff` genuinely sounds brighter, not just louder.

## 2.4 A chord — three notes struck together

`play/chord` takes a list of notes and strikes them at the same
instant. The result is the piano's characteristic full-bodied
harmony: three separate strikes that ring into a single sonority.

```scheme
(begin
  (synth/select 'grand-piano)
  (play/dynamics! 'mf)
  (play/chord '(c4 e4 g4) 'half))
```

A C-major chord. Three notes, same instant, half-beat duration.
You hear the chord as a single event — but if you listen closely to
the onset, you can hear three distinct strikes tightly stacked. That
tightness is the piano's harmonic weld: the same hammer mechanism
produces every note, so their onsets align.

## 2.5 The sustain pedal — hold the notes ringing

The pedal is what makes the piano *sing*. When the pedal is down,
notes do not damp when their durations expire — they keep ringing
until you release the pedal. This is the defining piano articulation.

```scheme
(begin
  (synth/select 'grand-piano)
  (synth/pedal! 'sustain #t)
  (play/note 'c4 'eighth)
  (play/note 'e4 'eighth)
  (play/note 'g4 'eighth)
  (play/note 'c5 'eighth)
  (synth/pedal! 'sustain #f))
```

Four short notes played in sequence with the pedal down. Even though
each note is only an eighth beat long, they all keep ringing —
because the pedal has kept every damper up. When you release the
pedal on the last line, all four notes damp at once. This is the
\"blooming chord from a scale\" pattern: play a melodic figure with
the pedal down and every note becomes a chord tone.

## 2.6 A pedaled arpeggio into a chord

Combining 2.4 and 2.5. Play an arpeggio (chord notes one at a time)
with the pedal down; the individual notes accumulate into the chord.
Then release the pedal to damp them all.

```scheme
(begin
  (synth/select 'grand-piano)
  (synth/pedal! 'sustain #t)
  (in-order
    (play/note 'c3 'eighth)
    (play/note 'g3 'eighth)
    (play/note 'e4 'eighth)
    (play/note 'c5 'eighth))
  (synth/pedal! 'sustain #f)
  (play/chord '(c3 g3 e4 c5) 'half))
```

You hear a low-to-high roll — each note ringing on top of the last —
into a full ringing chord. Then a beat of silence (the pedal came
up). Then the same four notes struck together as a chord. Same
notes, two ways of getting there: rolled and pedaled, versus struck
together. The first has motion; the second has weight.

## 2.7 A short piano piece — everything so far

Combine articulation, dynamics, pedal, and chord into one small
piece. The piano is the instrument where a lot of decisions collide
in one voice; this is a taste of how they layer.

```scheme
(begin
  (tempo 72)
  (synth/select 'grand-piano)
  (play/articulation! 'legato)
  (play/dynamics! 'mp)
  (synth/pedal! 'sustain #t)
  (in-order
    (play/note 'c4 'quarter)
    (play/note 'e4 'quarter)
    (play/note 'g4 'quarter)
    (play/note 'c5 'half)
    (rest 'eighth)
    (play/chord '(c3 g3 e4 c5) 'whole))
  (synth/pedal! 'sustain #f))
```

Slow tempo. Legato. Middle dynamic. Pedal down through the whole
thing. A rising line to C5, a breath of rest, and a full pedaled
chord to close. That is a piano gesture. Change the dynamic to `ff`
and the same eight tokens turn into a bold declaration. Change it to
`pp` and it becomes a whispered thought. The pedal stays; the
gesture changes.

*If I could give a beginning piano composer one piece of advice
about writing for the instrument in Motoi Scheme, it would be
this: the pedal is not a special effect. The pedal is the default
posture of the piano when it is being expressive. Write with the
pedal down. Damp when the harmony needs to change. That is the
shape of most piano music you love.*

> **Under the hood**
>
> The grand-piano profile is a physical-model hammered-string synth.
> Each note is a strike event on a modeled string with tension and
> mass parameters tuned per pitch. The strike excites the string,
> and the resulting waveform is a sum of decaying partials (a
> fundamental plus harmonics that fade at different rates — high
> partials fade fastest). The sustain pedal disables the per-note
> damper on all strings simultaneously, so decays extend until
> the pedal is released. Dynamics scale the strike velocity, which
> affects both amplitude and the amplitude ratio between the
> fundamental and its high partials — that is why `ff` is
> genuinely brighter, not just louder.

## What you know now

- The piano is synthesized by a physical-model hammered-string
  profile.
- `play/note` on the piano is a hammer strike with a decay.
- `play/articulation!` chooses between natural, legato, and staccato
  — the onset and sustain of the strike.
- `play/dynamics!` scales the strike velocity; `ff` is louder *and*
  brighter than `pp`.
- `play/chord` strikes multiple notes at the same instant.
- `synth/pedal! 'sustain #t` releases dampers so notes ring across
  their scheduled durations.
- The pedal is the expressive default posture, not a special effect.

